         <abstract>
            <p>Approximation of $f'(x)$ by a difference quotient of the form $$h^{-1}\lbrack a_1f(x + b_1h) + a_2f(x + b_2h) + a_3f(x + b_3h) \rbrack$$ is found to be optimized for a wide class of real-valued functions by the surprisingly asymmetric choice of $\mathbf{b} = (b_1, b_2, b_3) = (1/\sqrt3 - 1, 1/\sqrt3, 1/\sqrt3 + 1)$. The nearly optimal choice of $\mathbf{b} = (-2, 3, 6)$ is also discussed.</p>
          </abstract>
